message:
Thanks a lot for the great articles! I am facing a problem now using the NotifyTaskCompletion and had no luck finding a solution. I have a collection of ViewModels which have a property of the INotifyTaskCompletion<string>. I Have the values bound to the view like in the article and in the parent ViewModel that holds this collection of child VMs I have a foreach loop like this:

foreach (var movie in movies)  
 {  
 var movieListItem = new MovieListItemViewModel(movie);  
 movieListItem.ImageSource = NotifyTaskCompletion.Create(imageLoader.GetImageUrl(movie.Name));  
 MovieListItems.Add(movieListItem);  
 }  
The problem is the GetImageUrl method calls an API that limits concurrent requests. Using this loop, all the requests are run at once and return errors. If I put a Thread.Sleep in the loop, the requests are run one by one and complete successfully, but of course since it is put in the constructor of the VM, it only shows up after all requests are done.  
How could I go about limiting the requests to be made one or two at a time in this scenario? Should I modify NotifyTaskCompletion and try to implement a delay there, or do you see a better approach that dumb old me does not see?   
Thanks again for sharing the awesome AsyncEx project!

I managed to at least make it work by adding a throttling in my ImageLoader class, though it is pretty ugly. I used a static variable to hold the amount of concurrent requests and modified my async method like so:

public async Task<string> GetImageUrl(string movie)  
{  
 while (CurrentRequests > 2) //only accept at most 3 concurrent requests  
 {  
 await Dummy();  
 }

 CurrentRequests++;   
var document = await GetMovieHtml(movie);  
CurrentRequests--;

 //Rest of method....  
 }  
The Dummy method is a simple await Task.Delay(200)  
While this worked I am not happy with this solution and would welcome suggestions of a better way to solve it!

Hi Steven,

Thank you very much for the link. But unfortunately I can't use .NET 4.6. I tried to use it with .Net 4.5.1, but had no success.  
What I figured out is that I can use my normal relay command which takes a parameter and do something like this:

public ICommand StoreSelectedCommand  
{  
get   
{  
 if (this._storeSelectedCommand == null)  
{  
 this._storeSelectedCommand = new RelayCommand<unit>(  
async (commandParameter) =>{ await Task.Run(() => StoreSelectedAsync(commandParameter)); }  
);  
 }  
 return this._storeSelectedCommand;  
 }  
}

My exception handling is done in the called procedure.

Thanks again to Michigan, where I spent three wonderful years.

No, you don't. This will work fine:

try  
{  
 await SomethingAsync();  
}  
catch (Exception ex)  
{  
 ShowModalErrorDialog(ex);  
}

Isn't the await inside the NotificationTaskCompletion object?

Command = AsyncCommand.Create(MethodThatReturnsATask);

private Task MethodThatReturnsATask()  
 {  
 return Task.Run(() =>  
 {  
 try  
 {  
 // fetch data from service  
 }  
 catch (Exception e)  
 {  
 string err = "Cannot get data";  
 Logger.Error(err, e);  
 dispatcher.InvokeAsync(() =>  
 {  
_dialogService.ShowError(e);  
 });  
 }  
 });  
 }

Yes, you are correct. Sorry, I read through that code too quickly and missed that. If the try/catch is inside the Task.Run, then it will be on a thread pool thread. You can move the try/catch to be outside the Task.Run, and then it will be on the UI thread:

private async Task MethodThatReturnsATask()  
{  
try  
{  
await Task.Run(() =>  
{  
// fetch data from service  
});  
}  
catch (Exception e)  
{  
string err = "Cannot get data";  
Logger.Error(err, e);  
_dialogService.ShowError(e);  
}  
}
